<TEXT>
a huge plastic recycling center will open 
this fall to reuse all the cheeseburger holders foam coffee cups 
and other fastfood detritus from restaurants hospitals and 
schools officials said friday 
this a positive step for the environment and for southern 
california said e james schneiders president and chief 
executive officer of the national polystyrene recycling co we 
know people here want to recycle polystyrene and we are making that 
possible 
the company will own the 55000squarefoot plant currently 
under construction in corona a western suburb and talco recycling 
inc will operate it said schneiders it will open in october 
the company also is planning to open centers in the san 
francisco chicago and philadelphia metropolitan areas by the end 
of this year schneiders said 
schneiders and talco president and owner john shedd announced 
the new center at wadsworth elementary school where students 
participate in a program to recycle lunch trays made of polystyrene 
students from 17 los angeles unified school district campuses 
have recycled more than 15 million foam lunch trays 
national polystyrene opened the first polystyrene recycling 
center in the united states plastics again the plant in 
leominster mass can recycle up to 3 million pounds of used 
polystyrene annually 
the corona plant will be able to recycle more than 13 million 
pounds of drink cups plates and eating utensils along with 
nonfood packing products such as packaging foam and foam 
containers 
the plant will pay four cents a pound for polystyrene materials 
although individuals can drop off their used molded plastic center 
officials expect most clients will be companies and institutions 
such as hospitals schools and fastfood restaurants 
at the plant the materials will be washed ground rinsed and 
then melted down the material will then be formed into long 
spaghettilike strips run through a cold water bath and chopped 
into little pellets 
the pellets can be resold to companies that make polystyrene 
products 
polystyrene had been recycled for years before recycling 
became a public issue schneiders said what is new now is the 
postconsumer recycling of polystyrene 
maybe eventually curbside pickup programs will include 
polystyrene along with aluminum cans newspapers and glass 
bottles he said we sure would like that 
</TEXT>
