<TEXT>
the navy will continue underwater explosive tests 
off key west a military official said friday despite a 
confrontation with two dolphin lovers that led to a 10 million 
lawsuit and a federal investigation 
several more tests are planned but times and locations are 
secret said joe cody a spokesman for the naval air development 
center a wing of the navy that develops aircraft systems and other 
military components 
some environmentalists claim the tests harm dolphins and 
threaten fragile coral reefs 
on thursday two animal rights activists who claim they were 
rammed by boats during a protest last week filed a 10 million suit 
against private companies hired by the navy to carry personnel and 
equipment for the tests 
the dade circuit court suit by russel rector and richard obarry 
claims they were struck by vessels from miamibased moby marine 
corp and general offshore corp of key west the two companies are 
charged with assault intentional infliction of bodily harm and 
negligence 
officials at both companies said friday they had not seen the 
suit and could not comment they were hired to take part in the 
tests by the navy 
cody speaking from the development centers headquarters in 
warminster pa said an attorney has been assigned to the case he 
had no further comment 
the fbi said it was also looking into the allegations from 
rector and obarry who trained a dolphin that appeared on the 
1960s television show flipper 
hospital records indicate the men suffered bruises and sprains 
obarry had a concussion 
they had swum into the test area to try to block the test of the 
1200pound explosive which in fact already had been detonated 
obarry halted an earlier test by hanging onto a buoy in the 
offlimits zone 
</TEXT>
