<TEXT>
with seven iraqi divisions in kuwait and another 
24 near the iraqsaudi border european and israeli military 
analysts say a usled military operation to liberate kuwait would 
be outnumbered and outgunned 
the best option for the moment the experts say is to go on 
barricading the ports of iraq and its friends 
they say the forces now assembling in saudi arabia should dig 
in trust their superior weapons to deter further iraqi aggression 
and wait for iraq to make the first move 
but the problem is tension is growing because iraq is now able 
to move more forces across the border said paul beaver 
publisher of janes defense weekly 
the risk of escalation is there because there are going to be 
so many forces in saudi most of whom cant talk to the other 
usually a recipe for disaster he said in an interview thursday 
according to janes latest estimates iraq has seven divisions 
in kuwait and 24 on the iraqisaudi border were talking of them 
having available now south of baghdad 400000 soldiers beaver 
said 
with a flight landing in saudi arabia every seven minutes the 
us military force is approaching 50000 janes estimates 
but col andrew duncan of the international institute of 
strategic studies estimated it would take a sixmonth buildup of 
us forces to be strong enough to oust the iraqis from kuwait 
he said the americans currently have only a few old light 
sheridan tanks in saudi arabia and would need heavy armor for any 
serious push 
i would say its pie in the sky to say theres any military 
option to invade kuwait duncan said the united states would 
have less than one mechanized division there by september and 
would need at least five to push the iraqis out and keep them out 
he said 
francis tusa european editor of armed forces journal 
international said another question was whether the saudis would 
allow 250000 or 300000 us troops on their soil given the 
opposition of many arabs to the american presence in the middle 
east 
i would hang back i would let the iraqis make the first move 
and let them make a serious move he said the iraqis 
politically speaking have to do something pretty flagrant and 
massive before the arabs will be happy with a us response 
dore gold a senior analyst at tel aviv universitys jaffee 
center for strategic studies said the main american option would 
be a massive air attack on the iraqi military infrastructure 
but most do not believe that you can use the air force to 
force ground troops to retreat he said 
beaver said many military strategists believe air attacks 
against economic targets like power stations and desalination 
plants would work 
but the ramifications are at present far too fraught for the 
americans to contemplate he said 
ian anthony a researcher at the stockholm international peace 
research institute said the us air force could also hit 
strategic targets like highways that channel supplies from jordan 
to iraq 
but neither side is eager to escalate the conflict he said 
because for either side now the next step is likely to have 
extremely serious consequences 
dore said another reason for holding off on action now is that 
both sides believe time is on their side 
the us believes that the sanctions against iraq will be felt 
in several months while iraq feels that the larger mercantile 
international system will start to cheat in a few months time and 
the enthusiastic arab national support for saddam hussein will 
eventually undermine economic sanctions he said 
the one thing the multinational force can do is effectively 
blockade ports beaver said 
that means mersin in southern turkey aqaba in jordan and of 
course the neck of the gulf or the straits of hormuz to prevent 
iraqi traffic going in and out he said 
but beaver added that iraqs sudden decision to settle the 
eightyear war with iran could rupture the stranglehold if tehran 
opens its border with iraq 
