<TEXT>
the spirit of albert schweitzer has 
found an unlikely home on a quiet street in connecticut thousands 
of miles from the african village where the late theologian 
philosopher and doctor spent much of his life as a medical 
missionary 
inside the albert schweitzer memorial foundation large black 
and white portraits of the nobel peace prizewinner stare down from 
the walls interspersed with printed quotations from his work 
relics of his life crowd the firstfloor rooms of the small 
house including busts of schweitzer with his craggy mustachioed 
face and a book the great humanitarian inscribed to maria 
lagendijk the dutch nurse who worked with him at his hospital in 
lambarene a small village in the west african country of gabon 
you know how as young people you always find a hero a star 
you can cling to thats exactly how it was for me said harold 
robles the foundations director recalling the time when he 
learned of schweitzer as a boy in a classroom in rotterdam holland 
robles an international telemarketing executive who moved to 
the united states in 1981 turned his lifelong fascination with 
schweitzer into a public monument when he established the 
foundation in 1983 
his collection today is used by schweitzer scholars from around 
the world 
but robles said his greatest contribution to schweitzers memory 
will occur in new york thursday with the start of the twoday 
international albert schweitzer colloquium at the united nations 
robles spent 2 years organizing the colloquium timed for the 25th 
anniversary of schweitzers death on sept 4 1965 at the age of 
90 
such renowned figures as noble peace prize winners oscar arias 
sanchez elie wiesel and linus pauling will speak on the 
relevance of albert schweitzer at the dawn of the 21st century 
rhena schweitzer miller schweitzers daughter is serving as an 
honorary chairwoman 
she said the gathering which already has attracted nearly 700 
people will help people see the continuing relevance of her 
fathers philosophy 
he talked about many things before his time she said 
reciting his interest in such contemporary issues as the 
environment and nuclear war 
because of the west african hospital he designed and built in 
1913 schweitzer is known to most people as a famous doctor robles 
said he spent most of his life in the remote village establishing 
a leper colony and a large general practice 
but schweitzer had numerous other accomplishments that are less 
widely known his book the quest of the historical jesus 
influenced a generation of theologians a gifted musician 
schweitzer wrote a groundbreaking biography of johann sebastian 
bach in 1905 and published bachs complete organ works because he 
also was an organist 
but in his own mind schweitzer seems to have thought of himself 
first and foremost as a philosopher said robles 
in a quotation robles is particularly fond of schweitzer said 
when you portray me it should not be as the doctor who ministers 
to the sick it is my philosophy of reverence for life that i 
consider my primary contribution to the world 
robles first wrote to his hero when he was 8 schweitzer wrote 
back telling him to study hard and finish his schoolwork before 
making any great plans to come to africa 
robles continued to write to the hospital beginning what was to 
be a lifelong correspondence with lagendijk the nurse who was 
working with schweitzer in africa the woman would write on 
schweitzers behalf and pass on requests from the young boy 
when schweitzer visited rotterdam when robles was 11 lagendijk 
made sure the boy was on the list of those to meet him 
robles said people always are amazed by the fact that he 
remembers little of this one facetoface encounter he had with his 
hero 
the way i met schweitzer and the way i admire him and came to 
know him is through his books robles said i read him over and 
over and over again and that is how i met the man 
</TEXT>
