<TEXT>
if a guy cant hit it off with those 
sunbaked southern california females who like to play in the surf 
he can always go back to san francisco and sit on the dock of the 
bay 
especially if hes a sea lion 
last year hundreds of squatters with fish breath descended on a 
dock near the citys famed fishermans wharf tourist attraction and 
made themselves at home now many are back 
the 100 or so sea lions on pier 39 are just a bunch of really 
lonely guys said ann maurer of the california marine mammal 
center in marin county they are young males that couldnt 
establish themselves with females during the mating season in the 
channel islands off santa barbara she said 
except for a lack of sea lionesses the pier is everything a 
sea lion could ask for maurer said as far as the sea lions 
are concerned k dock is just another strip of beach with plenty of 
sun and a lot of fish just over the side 
their choice of residence brings them in close contact with 
humans many who have never seen the lumbering ocean mammals 
outside a zoo 
the barking sometimes pushy sea lions are protected under the 
federal marine mammals protective act and may not be harassed 
hunted captured or killed 
about 300 of the animals that can weigh up to 800 pounds took up 
residence on pier 39 last year with most departing by spring they 
began returning last weekend peigin barrett executive director of 
the marine center said friday they come and go with the fishing 
and breeding seasons she said whats unusual is to see them 
in one place and so close to humans they are only about eight feet 
away with just a railing separating them from people 
business owners for pier 39 which contains tourist shops and 
amusement arcades called the marine center for help when sea lions 
started congregating at the dock last year neighbors complained 
about all the noise from the animals barrett said 
ultimately the sea lions were simply left alone the pugnacious 
critters are not intimidated by the boat people who normally 
inhabit the 20 or so berths on the dock the harbors managers 
moved the boats for the duration of their seasonal visit 
we give them that dock when they show up move out boats to 
other docks said pier 39 spokeswoman alicia vargas its live 
and let live and as long as weve got the space to spare theyre 
welcome to it besides theyre kind of cute and the tourists like 
them 
barrett said the sea lion invasion can teach people more about 
sea life 
people get a close look at the sea lions it is very 
educational she said there were several sea lions that had 
fishing debris around their necks and the public could see the 
damage caused by carelessness 
the current complement is likely to stay until springtime then 
try their luck again next year in mating competition on the islands 
get used to it barrett said as far as the sea lions are 
concerned pier 39 is home 
