<TEXT>
the energy departments delay in announcing 
its revised cost of the superconducting super collider amid reports 
of a 3 billion jump confirms that the atomsmasher project is 
way out of control a congressional critic charges 
the announcement had been expected friday but the energy 
department said the four groups making the estimates are still 
working out differences the revised figure would be ready by sept 
7 the department said 
in a letter to rep robert roe dnj chairman of the house 
science space and technology committee deputy energy secretary 
henson moore said the reconciliation process is still under 
way he gave no more explanation 
on july 25 moore said the four groups would try to have a final 
figure aug 17 
preliminary estimates of three of the groups were around 8 
billion a fourth estimate prepared by a group under doe contract 
but acting independently is between 115 billion and 117 
billion the newsletter inside energy reported the department has 
not confirmed the estimate 
usually only three groups of estimators work on doe projects 
the previous highest figure 86 billion was made last month 
by the group of scientists that redesigned the collider for a 
nearly a year doe planners have said it would cost about 8 
billion when first proposed in the mid1980s the collider was 
estimated to cost 44 billion 
delaying reports and rising costs confirm the suspicion this 
project is way out of control and very likely to run into serious 
budgetary questions said rep dennis eckart dohio a leading 
opponent of the new machine 
i grow more confident each day the collider wont survive 
he said 
the spiraling cost has been one of the main arguments eckart and 
other congressional opponents have used against the atom smasher 
to be built south of dallas 
congress has appropriated 318 million including funds to start 
construction for next year but that could be jeopardized because 
of the higher estimate eckart said 
given the ineptitude in giving us accurate cost estimates and 
facing a real budget summit that will make major cuts across 
the board the ssc may have just priced itself out of existence 
he said 
with the 8 billion figure in mind the house in may capped the 
colliders federal funds at 5 billion for the next five years 
texas has pledged 1 billion the rest is expected to come from 
foreign investors and other sources 
the three preliminary estimates agreed on the costs of building 
the 54mile tunnel and the superconducting magnets they varied in 
the cost of potential delays 
the independent group says the collider alone will cost 97 
billion and that detectors the giant microscopes that record 
atomic collisions will cost another 2 billion inside energy 
reported moore told the newsletter the group may have thought more 
detectors are needed 
but members of the texas delegation said the colliders funding 
