<TEXT>
the soviet and west german foreign ministers say 
they have agreed on the main points of a german unification plan 
and that the allies may sign a treaty giving up control in less 
than a month 
we are going to change opinions about the future of united 
germany and the soviet union foreign minister eduard a 
shevardnadze predicted at a joint news conference friday with west 
german foreign minister hansdietrich genscher 
the new treaty will cover cooperation in the economy trade 
science technology culture and soviet troops stationed in former 
communist east germany shevardnadze said 
the soviet foreign minister said he expects to initial and 
possibly sign the final document giving up the four allies 
authority over germany on sept 12 in moscow as scheduled 
shevardnadze and genscher said they agreed on the essence of the 
concluding document on external aspects of unification although a 
few final details remained shevardnadze said he expects the other 
parties in the twoplusfour talks to agree with their work 
the two are east germany and west germany and the four 
are the world war ii allied victors the soviet union the united 
states britain and france 
genscher said initialing of the twoplusfour document next 
month would show that there is no external reason to prevent german 
unification which he expects to occur oct 1314 
shevardnadze said the document might even be signed sept 12 
the four powers and the united germany then would be expected to 
ratify the treaty under their respective constitutional processes 
he said 
genscher said he expects west german chancellor helmut kohl to 
spell out details for the sovietgerman treaty proposal in a letter 
to soviet president mikhail s gorbachev which would be sent 
before the sept 12 meeting 
shevardnadze said the two sides also had agreed on material 
and financial concerns regarding the presence and withdrawal of 
soviet troops from east germany genscher said final details will 
be worked out in meetings between the soviet and west german 
finance ministers aug 24 
west germany has agreed to help pay for the soviet soldiers 
upkeep because the soviet union is short of convertible currency 
which is necessary now that east germany has switched to use of the 
west german mark 
cost of this agreement to west germany for the second half of 
this year is estimated to be 780 million genscher also said east 
germany and west germany will issue statements before sept 12 on 
their respective final troop ceilings 
gorbachev and kohl agreed at a meeting at a soviet mountain 
resort in july on the most difficult issues of german unification 
these included the united germanys membership in nato and 
reduction of its combined armed forces from 600000 to 370000 over 
three to four years 
the soviets agreed to withdraw their 380000 soldiers from east 
german territory in the same time period 
genscher said the two men also discussed the withdrawal of the 
four powers troops from berlin the earlier kohlgorbachev meeting 
decided that western soldiers could stay in berlin as long as 
soviet troops remained in east germany 
