<TEXT>
the 370000 red army soldiers in 
east germany have few military duties these days so they spend a 
lot of time deciding what to buy with the windfall west germany 
just handed them 
like east germans the soviet troopers were allowed to trade 
savings in east german marks for west german money when the 
currencies merged july 1 since then they have been paid in west 
german marks 
several recruits walking along a road outside potsdam on a hot 
summer day spoke with a western reporter about their new wealth 
and their plans for it 
dmitri wants a tape deck valery prefers a video recorder and 
alexei has his mind set on a car vladimir said he bought his niece 
really good gifts 
things are better for us now because we have west german marks 
and there are many things to buy said dmitri a 20yearold 
sergeant from the ukraine 
east germany pays the cost of keeping soviet troops in this 
former cornerstone of the warsaw pact the only difference now is 
that the money is paid in west german marks instead of the 
nowdefunct east mark 
a red army private gets only the equivalent of 15 a month a 
sergeant earns twice that and officers pay starts at about 625 a 
fortune in soviet terms 
at the black market rate in the soviet union even a privates 
pay is worth about 154 rubles more than half the average soviet 
monthly wage of 250 rubles 
in potsdam however it doesnt buy many 250 plates of herring 
washed down with 60cent colas and the first flush of spending has 
passed 
they are buying a lot less now said clark brutler who 
sells socks in the outdoor market they just dont have as much 
money anymore 
many have their eyes on luxury electronic goods or cars but 
even used cars are far beyond the means of lowranking soldiers 
some have sold weapons to raise cash for highpriced items 
so far this year west berlin police have confiscated 90 rifles 
pistols and revolvers 135 pounds of explosives 165 grenades and 
four grenade launchers they said most were of soviet origin 
among the places weapons were seized was a park in east germany 
just outside west berlin where police said soviet soldiers were 
selling arms to west berliners 
soviet military hats coats and badges are peddled to tourists 
at the brandenburg gate and the former us checkpoint charlie 
along the berlin wall 
the soviet military dismisses reports that ordinary soldiers can 
barely survive on their pay 
soldiers get everything medicine free cigarettes taken 
care of by the soviet state said major karen streltschemnya a 
political officer at the soviet mission in east berlin deutsche 
marks are for snacks not to live on 
soviet officers can afford to eat well in their villas on their 
wooded base surrounded by a high white wall their wives return 
from shopping trips with heaping baskets of west german hams 
cheeses and other delicacies 
most of the thousands of soviet soldiers assigned to potsdam 
live in barracks that wind along a twolane road leading west from 
the city their lives are relatively spartan but probably better 
than they can expect as civilians back home where unemployment is 
growing and housing is scarce 
several red army soldiers have deserted their units and gone to 
west germany whose liberal asylum laws may apply to them 
red star the soviet military newspaper declared recently that 
fleeing to west germany was desertion with all its resulting 
consequences 
asylum is an issue each one of us thinks about but it is up 
to each soldier to make his own decision said oleg a ukrainian 
private 
potsdam has not experienced the kind of antagonism toward soviet 
troops seen elsewhere in east germany since that countrys 
stalinist government collapsed in november 
in many communities signs like russen raus russians out 
are common renate kern who has lived next to soviet military 
personnel for 22 years said they are the best neighbors weve 
never had any trouble they stay for a few years and then go home 
</TEXT>
