<TEXT>
the hms rose the worlds largest sailing 
wooden ship is trolling through the great lakes as it marks its 
longest journey since being restored in a connecticut harbor five 
years ago 
the 18thcentury british warship replica a 500ton wonder with 
masts reaching 150 feet into the air docked in chicago earlier 
this month and is touring several wisconsin ports along lake 
michigan before returning to connecticut in late september 
in all the ship will cover 5000 miles far fewer than its 
namesake traveled when it crossed the atlantic to attack rebel 
colonies during the revolutionary war 
it has been a very huge success at the ports that its been 
in said ron sonntag spokesman for the milwaukeebased festival 
events inc which arranged the tour its a huge spectacle 
people dont have any idea how big it is until they get next to 
it 
the vessel measures 179 feet long and 14 stories tall 
hundreds of midwesterners flocked on friday to watch the ship as 
it sailed into the harbor at racine wis the spectators were 
rewarded with a full 24cannon salute 
its very impressive its something i never thought id 
get the chance to see im bringing the children so they can see 
it i dont want them to miss a wonderful vision of the past said 
susan penn 40 of highland park ill who traveled north to 
racine to see the ship 
the hms rose left the bridgeport conn harbor june 20 
sailing up the atlantic coast to the st lawrence seaway its stops 
have included cleveland detroit and chicago it arrives in 
milwaukee its last stop aug 27 
the history of the rose is incredible we have the distinction 
of having the largest wooden vessel that is operational in the 
world said its owner kaye williams of bridgeport conn 
the replica was built in 1970 incorporating a cannon and the 
keel salvaged from the wreck of the original hms rose built in 
1757 as the british navys main warship the british had scuttled 
the ship in the savannah ga harbor at the end of the 
revolutionary war to avoid capture by the french 
but the replica was allowed to decay williams bought it for 
70000 in 1985 and spent 13 million to restore it as part of his 
development of a marina and restaurant 
festival events inc paid 250000 to bring the ship to 
milwaukee for the fourth annual maritime festival scheduled aug 
30 through sept 3 organizers expect 600 visitors to tour the ship 
every hour as part of the 200000 people expected at the event 
the hms rose and its crew of 28 are expected to return to 
bridgeport sept 20 
williams said he hopes to take the ship to puerto rico in 1992 
and then to the olympics in barcelona spain the same year 
such long trips are rare for wooden vessels in modern times but 
williams is confident theres no better duty for his ship 
she had to go to sea the quote that comes to mind is only 
men and ships rot at the dock williams said a vessel will 
come back in better shape than when she left 
