<TEXT>
killers and rapists whose victims were white got 
more severe punishment than those whose victims were black or 
hispanic in a newspaper survey of sentencing in dallas county in 
1988 
a story in sundays dallas times herald said a review of cases 
that year showed a conviction for the murder of a white person 
resulted in an average prison sentence of 30 years that compared 
with 20 years for the murder of a black person and 12 years for a 
hispanic 
the rape of a white resulted in a median sentence of 10 years 
compared with two years for the rape of a black and five years for 
a hispanic 
the punishment almost doubled when the attacker and victim were 
of different races the newspaper reported 
except for such interracial crimes sentencing disparities were 
much less pronounced for attempted murder and aggravated assault 
the newspaper said 
david baldus an iowa law professor who has studied race effects 
in death penalty cases said the study suggests that whitevictim 
crime particularly rape is treated quite differently in 
dallas 
scott anderson president of the dallas county criminal bar 
association was more blunt 
the systems racist he said most people are struggling 
to overcome it but it exists it starts all the way down in the 
police department and goes all the way to the top of the district 
attorneys office 
district attorney john vance said texas should follow the lead 
of congress and 31 states that have reformed the sentencing process 
to eliminate unjustifiable disparities 
i think we need to take a real serious look at the federal 
system of sentencing guidelines and thats the only time ive 
ever said that in my life said vance through plea bargaining 
his office effectively sets punishment in more than 90 percent of 
such felonies 
in the study the times herald noted legal factors that affect 
punishment including previous felony convictions aggravating 
circumstances and multiple offenses punished by the same sentence 
judges prosecutors and legal experts propose numerous theories 
for the sentencing inequities including the quality of legal aid 
for indigent defendants the reluctance of minorities to testify 
and juryimposed sentencing 
a university of new mexico sociologist who has studied the 
criminal justice systems handling of rape says the unequal 
punishment in cases involving black and white victims is a vestige 
of slavery days 
at one point in our history rapes were treated differently by 
law if a black man raped a white woman and i think you still have 
lingering effects of that said gary lafree author of the 1989 
book rape and criminal justice 
state district judge pat mcdowell said the victims social 
status also was a factor in sentencing 
a prosecutor can make a much stronger argument in favor of 
severe punishment when the victim is an upstanding contributing 
member of the community than he can if the victim is a street 
person mcdowell said 
it really shouldnt be that way he said but 
unfortunately thats part of our society 
jury sentencing disparities reflect the kind of jurors we have 
in dallas county said lawyer adelfa b callejo 
subconsciously i think the attitude is that the life of a 
white person is worth more than the life of a black or hispanic 
she said but its not just in the courts its apparent in every 
aspect of life in dallas 
