<DOCNO> AP900818-0142 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
black patients wait an average of five months 
longer than whites for kidney transplants a newpaper investigation 
has found 
the federal government is investigating the disparity which 
stems partly from the fact that most donor organs come from whites 
the pittsburg press reported sunday because of slight racial 
differences in blood type and antigens donor organs are more 
likely to match those of the same race 
based on a review of 13888 kidney transplants nationwide in 
1988 and 1989 the newspaper found that black patients spent an 
average 14 months waiting for an organ on average white patients 
waited slightly less than nine months 
the study included only transplants using organs from braindead 
donors not living relatives whites accounted for 3144 of the 
3802 kidneys donated last year in the united states the newspaper 
said 
it cited data from the united network for organ sharing of 
richmond va which has a government contract to control the 
national organ procurement and transplantation network 
we are very concerned about this variance but we do and have 
always taken every possible safeguard to ensure that race never is 
an issue in the fair allocation of organs said dr james wolf 
unos president and director of the kidney transplant program at 
northwestern memorial hospital in chicago 
because most kidneys come from white donors characteristics of 
the white population appear more often in the donor pool 
the pattern of blood types and antigens varies slightly among 
races and hospitals always try to match donor to recipient as 
closely as possible to avoid rejection of a transplanted organ 
the newspaper said its study corresponds to preliminary data 
developed during an investigation by the us department of health 
and human services although the report is not expected to be 
released until december hhs secretary louis sullivan has referred 
to the findings in speeches this month 
sullivan said the government report will show blacks were 
waiting twice as long as whites and these differences remain 
even when blood type age immunological and locational factors are 
taken into account 
details of the hhs investigation are incomplete but it would 
call for a close inspection of the differences in waiting times 
that occur in the 230 hospitals doing kidney transplants 
nationwide said linda sheaffer director of the federal office of 
organ transplantation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

