<TEXT>
one of the strangest things about the socalled 
collapse of housing prices is that you cant detect it in some of 
the statistics its as if the numbers were added up incorrectly 
in the second quarter of the year for instance the median 
selling price of existing singlefamily houses was 34 percent 
above the figure for a year earlier in defiance you might say 
of the popular impression 
and a national association of realtors survey of existinghome 
sales revealed that secondquarter prices were higher than a year 
earlier in 70 of 98 metropolitan areas in some the price jumps 
were huge 
topping the list was the seattletacoma area where the 
secondquarter median price leaped 353 percent over the previous 
year honolulu where prices rose 332 percent and sacramento 
calif where the rise was 30 percent 
figures such as these prove again that many national averages 
and medians are hardly sound guides for measuring local markets 
unlike stocks and bonds where prices really are national real 
estate prices are strictly local 
what happens in portland ore where the median rose 158 
percent has little bearing on what happens in the 
middlesexsomersethunterdon nj area where the median price 
fell 95 percent steepest in the nation 
only one midwest metropolitan area recorded a decrease but four 
in the west 10 in the northeast and 11 in the south posted drops 
even within states there were differences new york fell 61 
percent albany rose 26 percent 
what the figures reveal clearly is that there indeed are regions 
of extreme price weakness but that these areas do not merge into a 
national collapse as so often is stated 
why therefore the sense among homeowners that the marketplace 
is a disaster 
for one thing excessively high hopes that led many sellers to 
overprice the inevitable price cut that followed might have left 
the price higher than a year earlier but the sense of money lost 
remains 
a lengthening of the time it takes to sell a house contributes 
to the feeling of a down market in some areas of the northeast the 
median selling time is close to 300 days vs a few weeks just four 
years ago 
adding to the feeling of a dead market is the more critical 
attitude of buyers they are more selective more patient more 
inclined to negotiate than to buy immediately and of course 
lenders are tighter than ever 
for those sellers who can bide their time the selling delay is 
hardly the disaster it is for those who must sell these are the 
sales that provide the anecdotal evidence of a market collapse 
they are not easily forgotten 
in many communities for example real estate agents advertise 
that they sold houses within a week after listing the suggestion 
being that they provided the seller with an extra measure of 
marketplace expertise 
query them and you find that the seller urgently required a 
quick sale and that the listing agent priced the house well below 
market patient buyers learn a lot about pricing and often act 
quickly when they spot a steal 
no amount of statistical evidence is likely to dispel the notion 
that there has been a national housing price collapse too many 
people have indeed been hurt financially and millions of others 
are unnerved on hearing about them 
but so far the national housing disaster you hear so much about 
has happened more in the mind than in the numbers 
</TEXT>
