<TEXT>
chicagos giant commodity exchanges are readying their 
longdelayed japanese financial futures products for a september 
launch but they concede they have no hope of becoming the world 
leaders in those markets 
that distinction belongs to and will continue to belong to two 
japanese stock exchanges that have been trading futures on the 
nikkei 225 and topix stock indexes for nearly two years and on 
japanese government bonds for even longer 
the chicago exchanges say they will settle for being secondary 
markets it is a role to which they are not accustomed but which 
will nevertheless reinforce their presence in the global financial 
marketplace 
with a nikkei 225 contract available for trading in north 
america investors in the japanese stock market will have a means 
of protection after their regular trading day ends said john 
geldermann chairman of the mercs board of governors 
on sept 25 the merc will launch its nikkei 225 futures and 
futuresoptions contracts followed two days later by the board of 
trades introduction of futures and futuresoptions on the topix 
stock index and japanese government bonds 
the contracts will give investors mainly large institutional 
investors more places in which to essentially buy insurance 
against losses on japanese stocks and bonds 
the chicago markets are not likely to generate as much volume as 
their japanese counterparts though because they will be open for 
trading mainly during the us business day which is nighttime in 
japan 
spokesman michael oconnell said the board of trade also will 
list its japanese products for trading during the exchanges 
2hour evening session which corresponds to the opening of the 
japanese trading day 
futures on the nikkei 225 japans version of the dow jones 
industrial average are traded on the osaka securities exchange 
the topix is an index based on all 1100 stocks listed on the 
tokyo stock exchange the worlds largest the tokyo exchange 
trades topix futures and japanese government bond futures 
the futures are contracts to buy or sell stocks and bonds at 
some future date at a price agreed upon in advance investors can 
use the contracts to offset their risk in the underlying cash 
markets or speculate on market movements 
strategists at the chicago board of trade and the chicago 
mercantile exchange began designing the new products at least five 
years ago at a time when japanese laws forbade financial futures 
trading on japanese exchanges 
the chicago exchanges hoped to capitalize on the situation by 
creating their own riskmanagement tools for japanese investors as 
well as for others who invest in the japanese financial markets 
the potential rewards were enormous as the chicago exchanges 
already had proven with the remarkable success of their us 
government bond and stockindex futures 
those products transformed the merc and board of trade from 
sleepy agricultural commodity markets to worldclass financial 
exchanges 
the chicago exchanges won us regulatory approval for the 
contracts in 1988 at about the same time that the japanese 
government relaxed restrictions on such products at home 
the result was that the chicago exchanges helped the japanese 
develop their own markets for financial futures in exchange for the 
rights to trade those same contracts in the united states 
oconnell said the board of trade considers it important to 
offer the contracts even though the exchange has no expectation of 
overtaking the japanese markets in trading volume 
with the marketplace becoming so international in scope it 
behooves us to compete on the international scene he said 
oconnell said the exchange also plans to introduce futures on 
various european government bonds 
</TEXT>
