contained said marilyn schaja economist at donaldson lufkin 
and jenrette securities corp in new york it suggests there was 
some kind of preiraq problem 
the most troubling figure came from the labor department which 
said consumer prices rose 04 percent in july when oil prices were 
falling 
economists said this means when the full impact of rising oil 
prices is felt in august and beyond inflation could surge toward 
an annualized rate of 7 percent or more for 1990 
that would be the worst in nine years and underscore the growing 
us addiction to foreign oil which now accounts for half the 
countrys consumption of 17 million barrels a day 
oil is in every product and the price will be reflected in 
every single good said james chessen deputy director of policy 
development at the american bankers association in washington 
well see a significant rise im pretty worried about that 
one of the federal reserves principal jobs is to restrain 
inflation through its influence over interest rates pushing them 
up when inflation rises and easing when the economy slows 
before the july inflation numbers were revealed it was widely 
assumed that the federal open market committee the feds 
policymaking arm would take subtle steps to depress interest rates 
at a regular meeting this coming week but now many economists say 
they dont believe that will happen for a while 
further complicating the picture is the heavy debt burden the 
economy is carrying easing interest rates would only add to the 
toll being exacted by the budget deficit the savings amp loan 
bailout bankruptcies and high levels of corporate debt 
i think the fed is in an odd position now chessen said 
